00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:10.125
First, let me introduce you to
Marsha Aday, his wife, Gete

00:02:10.125 --> 00:02:13.140
Tebo, and six of their
seven children.

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:15.880
Marsha Aday is the tribal leader
of the Messa tribe and

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:18.640
lives on the flanks of Mount
Yero Wallo deep in the Amaro

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:20.080
Mountains of Ethiopia.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:22.270
I wasn't looking for Marsha
Aday exactly.

00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:24.330
I was looking for the
best storyteller.

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:28.220
I traveled for six hours that
day by car and by foot and for

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:30.840
two days previous to that
from Addis Ababa,

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:32.300
the capital of Ethiopia.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:35.950
And when I got to Mount Yero
Wallo, I walked through--

00:02:35.950 --> 00:02:38.070
it's basically the Switzerland
of Ethiopia.

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:40.060
You're walking through
shocks of Kelly green

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:41.400
false banana trees.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.700
The coffee trees, the wild
coffee trees, are growing with

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:48.170
such ferocity they seem to
sprout new leaves and coffee

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:49.580
cherries by the second.

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:51.520
When I got there, I asked
everyone and I said, who's the

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:53.150
best storyteller here?

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:56.640
And without long, I knew that I
was looking for Marsha Aday.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.800
Marsha Aday lives in a
home without a door.

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:01.580
That signifies his status as
the head of the tribe.

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:04.510
He's protected by everyone
around him.

00:03:04.510 --> 00:03:06.930
And he can also have full
vantage point of the

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:08.080
valley below him.

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:11.260
So he knew I was coming to talk
to him a full hour before

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:13.370
I even knew who he was
or where I was going.

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:14.530
He was getting ready.

00:03:14.530 --> 00:03:16.280
He was taking all of the
furniture out of his home and

00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:19.290
putting it outside, covering it
with skins and with furs to

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:20.790
make sure that we'd
be comfortable.

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:23.530
And when I finally arrived, we
sat down and started talking

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:25.340
about coffee.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:29.090
Marsha Aday is a coffee farmer
in one of the most rural parts

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:33.280
of Ethiopia, which means he
makes less than $1 a day.

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:37.330
However, he drinks a fortune
every day in coffee.

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:40.210
Coffee is so plentiful here in
Ethiopia that people have

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:41.185
coffee trees in their
backyard.

00:03:41.185 --> 00:03:43.610
They have coffee forests
in their backyard.

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:47.550
And they drink coffee so much
that if Marsha Aday's personal

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:51.760
coffee grove was getting top
value in the market, which is

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:57.670
about $150, $160 a pound, he
himself would drink $75 a day

00:03:57.670 --> 00:04:01.340
in coffee, which is a four month
income to him that he's

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:02.940
just drinking away
in his coffee.

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.195
So is he a poor Ethiopian
coffee farmer?

00:04:05.195 --> 00:04:07.860
Or is he a rich Ethiopian
coffee farmer?

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.250
Totally depends on how we're
willing to look at Ethiopia,

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:13.610
coffee, economics, any of it.

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:16.140
Coffee in the Amaro Mountains
didn't come here from people.

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:17.620
But it came here from nature.

00:04:17.620 --> 00:04:20.500
Wef Zerash is the term for
natural seed dispersal by

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:23.510
birds and by animals
in Ethiopia.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:26.520
And the coffee, as I said, is
so plentiful in this part of

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:29.400
Ethiopia that Marsha Aday likes
to say that there's no

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:32.370
way for the cherries
to leave the trees.

00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:35.880
His coffee is accounted for in
legend in Ethiopia in the 10th

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:37.210
century BC.

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:40.350
But Marsha Aday's ancestors
didn't start drinking it until

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:43.070
3,000 years later in
the 20th century.

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:45.060
And the story is told that they
were convinced that these

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:48.620
bright red coffee cherries, if
you would eat one of those,

00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:49.570
you would be burned.

00:04:49.570 --> 00:04:52.960
Because whatever was in it was
clearly going to explode in

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:53.880
your mouth.

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:59.460
And it wasn't until the mid
1900s where actually traders

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:01.570
came into the Amaro Mountains.

00:05:01.570 --> 00:05:04.930
They came on camels from the low
lands of Kerdea on camels

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:06.240
to the highlands of
the Amaro and

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:07.680
started trading for coffee.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:10.450
And Marsha Aday's ancestors
were like, hmm.

00:05:10.450 --> 00:05:11.230
What's going on here?

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:12.790
We thought these were
going to burn you.

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:16.420
And they waited until the same
traders returned, unburned,

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:19.190
before they started actually
consuming that coffee.

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:20.660
And once they did, it
was off the hook.

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:23.710
This coffee consumption is
like anywhere in Ethiopia

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:26.660
three times a day, four times a
day multiple cups of coffee.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:29.850
That's part of the every
day culture there.

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:31.920
Marsha Aday told me this story
while holding a bright red

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:34.080
coffee cherry in his hand
and handing it to me.

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:35.150
And I bit into it.

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:37.420
And when you bite into a ripe
one, your teeth kind of pierce

00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:38.450
the outer skin.

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:40.360
And I thought, what if this
could be the best

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:41.520
coffee in the world?

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:44.560
What if this is the coffee that
could also get that kind

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:46.440
of value on the market?

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:50.760
What would that mean for
these people here?

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.580
Marsha Aday lives a half a
drive away from any town,

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:55.570
assuming you can actually
drive on the roads.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:58.010
The roads are more often used
as flat spots for drying

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:00.205
coffee than they are for any
sort of transportation.

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:04.880
When you're actually driving
there, you have to stop and

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:07.130
let people move some of the
coffee away off the road.

00:06:07.130 --> 00:06:09.395
Because it's so unlikely to
have a vehicle show up.

00:06:09.395 --> 00:06:10.720
I was there for four days.

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.020
It was the only vehicle
we had.

00:06:12.020 --> 00:06:13.160
We almost didn't get out.

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:15.430
Because a huge flash flood
came in and made

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:16.360
everything a mud slide.

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:18.670
So we could have been there for
quite a bit longer before

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:21.130
another vehicle would've
been able to come up.

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:23.840
As I said, the coffee topples
over itself as it stretches up

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:25.910
the flanks of Mount
Yero Wallo.

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:28.370
Marsha Aday and I were speaking
for about a half an

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:29.180
hour at this point.

00:06:29.180 --> 00:06:30.190
And he was so excited.

00:06:30.190 --> 00:06:32.420
Because no one had ever asked
him about his coffee.

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:34.000
And to the best of his
knowledge, no one had ever

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:35.200
asked his ancestors.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.540
But he was sure, without a
doubt, that his coffee was the

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:40.580
best in Ethiopia.

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:43.630
And I've actually never met
anyone who thought differently

00:06:43.630 --> 00:06:45.570
about their coffee, right?

00:06:45.570 --> 00:06:46.830
And we were speaking.

00:06:46.830 --> 00:06:48.030
And he kept telling
me, my coffee

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:49.360
is the best in Ethiopia.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:52.030
And by the time he'd said it
three times, he was saying it

00:06:52.030 --> 00:06:53.220
to me in English.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:56.610
Because the translation had
computed at that point.

00:06:56.610 --> 00:07:00.690
And at that point, I said, well,
we're going to have to

00:07:00.690 --> 00:07:01.370
have some coffee.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:02.610
We're going to have to really
celebrate this.

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:03.120
And he said, yes.

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:04.910
But first, we should
kill an ox.

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:06.290
Because that's a logical
thing to do when

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:07.330
you're pretty excited.

00:07:07.330 --> 00:07:08.580
And you're in Ethiopia.

00:07:08.580 --> 00:07:10.570
And you're thinking, we should
have a celebration.

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:11.245
But it's the afternoon.

00:07:11.245 --> 00:07:12.740
And these clouds are mounting.

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:15.450
And actually grabbing the ox,
killing the ox, slaughtering

00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:17.150
it, cooking it, this
can take some time.

00:07:17.150 --> 00:07:18.040
We were a little bit pressed.

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:19.960
So we decided that the
alternative was that Marsha

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:21.255
Aday was going to
dance for me.

00:07:21.255 --> 00:07:22.650
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:23.900
