00:07:34.515 --> 00:07:37.170
MAJKA BURHARDT: This is his
costume for being the leader

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:39.350
of the Messa tribe that goes
back seven generations.

00:07:39.350 --> 00:07:41.150
And this his is pre-coffee
dance.

00:07:41.150 --> 00:07:42.350
He was really excited.

00:07:42.350 --> 00:07:45.430
So post-coffee, we're going
to amp it up a little bit.

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:48.720
And we went into his home to
find out what post-coffee was

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:49.200
going to be.

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:50.110
And we walked inside.

00:07:50.110 --> 00:07:52.230
And Gete Tebo was already
preparing coffee.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:54.010
So she had raw coffee beans.

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:56.220
They were over a charcoal
fire on a flat pan.

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:57.470
She's roasting them.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:08:01.020
All a sudden, that sweet smell
is infusing this earthen home.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:02.380
My stomach's growling.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:04.380
The clouds are building
in the east.

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:06.710
And then she takes
those perfectly

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:07.740
roasted coffee beans.

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:10.820
She puts them in a mortar and
pestle, takes her 30 seconds.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:12.800
I've been working in Ethiopia
for 10 years.

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:15.690
It takes me still about 35
minutes to do what it took her

00:08:15.690 --> 00:08:18.230
30 seconds to do to grind
those things by hand.

00:08:18.230 --> 00:08:20.580
Pours them into a thick-bellied
and thin-necked

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:21.860
jabana, a clay pot.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:23.030
Puts it on the stove.

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:25.490
And the smells just keep
infusing, sweet

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:26.940
and citrus and honey.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:28.520
And I keep thinking, God,
this is going to be

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:29.870
the best coffee ever.

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:31.560
And then this huge
clap of thunder

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:32.960
comes in and lightning.

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:35.020
And everything goes
dark in the home.

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:36.530
And I take one last breath.

00:08:36.530 --> 00:08:40.130
And I run as fast as I can
to escape a flash flood.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:43.710
And I never had that coffee.

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:48.230
70% of Ethiopia lies
between 2,000 and

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:49.790
8,000 feet in elevation.

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:53.660
50% of Ethiopia is incredibly
vegetated, moist, dark

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:54.510
volcanic soil.

00:08:54.510 --> 00:08:57.120
It's the perfect place
for growing coffee.

00:08:57.120 --> 00:09:00.280
The images we're used to seeing
of Ethiopia, dry,

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:01.350
barren desert.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:03.740
That's only a third
of Ethiopia.

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:06.220
This is the land where
humanity began.

00:09:06.220 --> 00:09:08.910
And if you listen to legend,
coffee showed up right after

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:13.010
humans and in fact in
the sixth century.

00:09:13.010 --> 00:09:19.000
Ethiopia has 10,000 different
types of coffee, 10,000 unique

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.520
flavors, varietals.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:23.950
And at this point, the
estimation is that only half

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:26.910
of them have actually been
found, tasted, and cataloged.

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:29.980
So 5,000 different types of
coffees are still lying in

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:32.360
wait in the forest
in Ethiopia.

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:35.800
That's incredibly intoxicating
for any sort of coffee

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:39.270
aficionado, entrepreneur to say,
what does it mean that

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:41.420
this country, one of the poorest
countries in the

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:44.810
world, has the greatest supply
of one of the globe's richest

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:45.720
commodities?

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:48.470
What can we do to kind of
push that together?

00:09:48.470 --> 00:09:52.750
What can we do to take those
tastes out of the forest?

00:09:52.750 --> 00:09:55.270
Ethiopia, over 60%
of its foreign

00:09:55.270 --> 00:09:56.780
earnings come from coffee.

00:09:56.780 --> 00:10:00.310
If you gave every coffee farmer
in Ethiopia 10 cents

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:04.100
more, Ethiopia's annual income
from coffee would go by $60

00:10:04.100 --> 00:10:05.390
million a year.

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:07.350
But I don't think that's
a really good idea.

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:10.040
Because Ethiopia is also kind
of this bastion, has been a

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:11.050
bastion of aid.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:12.600
It's been the largest
recipient of aid in

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:14.970
sub-Saharan Africa
since the '80s.

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:17.590
It's been the place where great
failures of aid have

00:10:17.590 --> 00:10:19.920
happened and great successes
of current sustainable

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:20.950
development.

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.230
And if we go in from a coffee
perspective and just say,

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:25.930
let's pay more to Ethiopia
because it's Ethiopian coffee.

00:10:25.930 --> 00:10:26.760
And we bet it's good.

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:28.570
We're going to be doing the
same thing by going in

00:10:28.570 --> 00:10:29.720
with a blind eye.

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:31.850
And I think what will be more
interesting and what's

00:10:31.850 --> 00:10:34.970
starting to happen is to go into
a nuanced conversation

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:36.670
about nuanced coffee.

00:10:36.670 --> 00:10:38.510
So here we are in California.

00:10:38.510 --> 00:10:41.380
You all have probably been in
restaurants or in cafes when

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.630
you walk in, you actually get
a bit of a coffee menu.

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:45.250
And you know that there
are different tastes.

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:47.740
There are different flavor
profiles for coffee.

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:50.390
Imagine if you went to the best
restaurant in Palo Alto.

00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:53.040
And the coffee list was as
big as the wine list.

00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:55.360
That's the potential we're
talking about.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:58.620
And if we do that, then suddenly
you're rewarding

00:10:58.620 --> 00:10:59.920
quality and taste.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:02.460
And you're actually entering
a complicated conversation,

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.950
which is where things, in my
opinion, start to get a lot

00:11:04.950 --> 00:11:06.200
more interesting.

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:10.740
This is what we're used to
seeing about Ethiopia,

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:12.050
drought, famine, poverty.

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.910
It's a constant and consumate
negative trifecta.

00:11:15.910 --> 00:11:18.520
I think coffee can actually
change this.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:21.490
And I think it can do it because
I'm kind of addicted

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:22.260
to complexity.

00:11:22.260 --> 00:11:23.750
And I think that this
is probably a crew--

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:27.060
people at Google are thinking.

00:11:27.060 --> 00:11:28.220
People are striving.

00:11:28.220 --> 00:11:31.420
And it's like, instead of going
towards a simple life,

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:33.830
how can we go towards a complex
life in the way that

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:35.590
we interact with the world?

00:11:35.590 --> 00:11:39.360
For me, it started simply
with a free latte.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:40.400
We're going to go back
in time here.

00:11:40.400 --> 00:11:41.980
So it's 2007.

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:44.630
And I was going to my
neighborhood coffee shop.

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:47.200
And there's this creepy guy
outside whispering to me,

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:48.390
which I'm not sure
about you all.

00:11:48.390 --> 00:11:51.380
But whispering in public
to strangers, not cool.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:52.920
It's just not the way
you make friends.

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:54.520
But then I'm walking into
this coffee shop.

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:57.300
And this guy's like, hey, free
latte across the street.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:11:58.710
It's like, yeah, OK.

00:11:58.710 --> 00:11:59.110
That's great.

00:11:59.110 --> 00:11:59.460
You're weird.

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:00.310
Just kind of move away.

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:01.730
I'm going to go into
the coffee shop.

00:12:01.730 --> 00:12:02.910
No, free lattes.

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:04.660
I said, but I don't
drink lattes.

00:12:04.660 --> 00:12:05.940
He said, but they're free.

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:08.620
It's like, that's a
pretty good point.

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:09.600
And then I look across
the street.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:11.810
And this kind of smoking
handsome man was serving up

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:12.430
the free coffee.

00:12:12.430 --> 00:12:14.730
So I was like, all right,
the free latte is

00:12:14.730 --> 00:12:15.540
looking really good.

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:17.280
So I cruise across the street.

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:18.860
And I'm lactose intolerant.

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:21.270
So this is already not a good
idea to be doing this.

00:12:21.270 --> 00:12:21.810
But I go up there.

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:22.800
And I get a free latte.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:23.500
And I sit down.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:25.230
I start eavesdropping
on the conversation.

00:12:25.230 --> 00:12:26.760
It's a coffee company
called Novo.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:28.610
They're in the Front
Range of Colorado.

00:12:28.610 --> 00:12:31.050
And they start talking about a
coffee called geisha that was

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:33.740
at that time getting $150
a pound on the market.

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:34.840
That's grown in Panama.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:36.690
And they were going on a trip
to try to find the genetic

00:12:36.690 --> 00:12:37.760
roots of it in Ethiopia.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:39.310
It took me about 30 seconds.

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:39.940
I stood up.

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:40.870
I introduced myself.

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:42.540
I'm like, do you guys
need a journalist?

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:45.080
Three months later,
I'm in Ethiopia.

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:49.290
When I got to Ethiopia, I
understood about 0.003% of the

00:12:49.290 --> 00:12:50.490
coffee world.

00:12:50.490 --> 00:12:51.690
I was a writer.

00:12:51.690 --> 00:12:53.625
I was an educated coffee
consumer to

00:12:53.625 --> 00:12:54.340
the best of my ability.

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:56.390
And I went into Ethiopia
being like, local,

00:12:56.390 --> 00:12:57.610
organic, fair trade.

00:12:57.610 --> 00:12:58.860
Those are what matters.

00:12:58.860 --> 00:12:59.900
And suddenly, I'm in Ethiopia.

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:03.510
And I'm like, whoa, I have no
idea what the heck I'm doing.

00:13:03.510 --> 00:13:05.280
This is completely
overwhelming.

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:07.900
And frankly, it was really
scary for me.

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:10.140
And so what I did is I turned to
a part of Ethiopia that was

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:11.730
way more comfortable for me.

00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:13.780
And that's because in my other
life, I'm a professional

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:16.335
climber, which I just got out of
the Wyoming wilderness and

00:13:16.335 --> 00:13:17.870
the winds where I was climbing
for seven days.

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:18.970
And we were laughing.

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:22.300
Because I'm covered in scratches
and scrapes because

00:13:22.300 --> 00:13:24.180
of shoving my hands into
granite cracks.

00:13:24.180 --> 00:13:27.050
So when I was in Ethiopia and I
was scared about coffee and

00:13:27.050 --> 00:13:29.420
I saw a picture of these towers
in northern Ethiopia, I

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:31.885
was like, yeah, that's
my home in Ethiopia.

00:13:31.885 --> 00:13:34.140
I'm going to go climbing
in Ethiopia.

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:36.620
An Ethiopian publisher caught
wind of this plan.

00:13:36.620 --> 00:13:38.090
And they came to me with
a plan of their own.

00:13:38.090 --> 00:13:39.660
And they're like, this
is super cool.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:40.530
You're going to go climbing.

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:41.080
You're a writer.

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:43.280
Why don't you write a book about
climbing in Ethiopia?

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:45.420
I was like, yeah, that
sounds great.

00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:47.480
And they said, and by writing
a book about climbing in

00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:49.980
Ethiopia, you're going
to save Ethiopia.

00:13:49.980 --> 00:13:51.230
So check it.

00:13:51.230 --> 00:13:52.120
You're a climber.

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:52.860
You're a writer.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:54.700
And someone tells you, if you
write a book about doing what

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:56.470
you love, you're going to save
one of the poorest countries

00:13:56.470 --> 00:13:57.620
in the world.

00:13:57.620 --> 00:13:58.650
That's a pretty good deal.

00:13:58.650 --> 00:13:59.780
That feels pretty good.

00:13:59.780 --> 00:14:00.870
So I was on board.

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:03.780
And the plan was that if I wrote
this book, that millions

00:14:03.780 --> 00:14:06.120
of climbers would then
flock to Ethiopia.

00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:08.280
And they'd change the economics
of Ethiopia.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.040
So a little show of hands, who
in the room is a climber?

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:12.170
OK, cool.

00:14:12.170 --> 00:14:14.460
And everybody else basically
knows what climbing is.

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:16.580
How many of you have flocked
to Ethiopia since my first

00:14:16.580 --> 00:14:18.140
book came out?

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:18.500
Awesome.

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:20.120
Everybody in the room raise
their hand just

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:21.660
for point of reference.

00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:23.380
So it was hard to pass up.

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:25.250
You think this could be
a really good idea.

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:26.070
And we got there.

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:28.290
And we showed up the
Gheralta massif--

00:14:28.290 --> 00:14:29.480
this is in northern Ethiopia.

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.120
It's never been climbed.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:33.990
We thought, we are so smart.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:35.360
Look, it-- we're so proud
of ourselves.

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:37.450
It was myself and a team
of four other women.

00:14:37.450 --> 00:14:40.310
And my friend Gabe Rogel was
shooting photos for the book.

00:14:40.310 --> 00:14:41.980
And we're like, no
one's been here.

00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:45.465
God, well how silly everybody
else is, how smart we are that

00:14:45.465 --> 00:14:46.700
we figured this out,
that we're the

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:48.150
ones discovering this.

00:14:48.150 --> 00:14:50.950
And we're in this landscape
in northern Ethiopia.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:53.670
This is the site of the
famine in the '80s.

00:14:53.670 --> 00:14:56.310
This is the place that was
hardest hit where millions

00:14:56.310 --> 00:14:58.580
starved, millions died.

00:14:58.580 --> 00:14:59.930
They were affected by political

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:02.110
power plays, food shortages.

00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:04.210
This is the heart of it
in northern Ethiopia.

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.150
And here we are climbing
there.

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:10.280
This is actually what pretty
much created aid as we all

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:11.500
know it in this room.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:14.640
Because in '84, you had this
really neat confluence where

00:15:14.640 --> 00:15:17.460
you had the fact that crisis
could be delivered direct to

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:19.070
our television sets at home.

00:15:19.070 --> 00:15:23.290
You had a very affluent US,
Canada, Western Europe ready

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:25.370
to help, ready to save things.

00:15:25.370 --> 00:15:28.770
And you had this dismal country
entrenched in famine.

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:30.820
And how could we not react?

00:15:30.820 --> 00:15:34.080
Most of us in this room have
probably been affected by that

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:35.770
part in 1984.

00:15:35.770 --> 00:15:39.120
I was 8 during the famine
in Ethiopia.

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:42.165
I was in Minneapolis
where I grew up.

00:15:42.165 --> 00:15:44.430
I went to Montessori school,
which is relevant.

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:47.170
Because when Michael Jackson,
Cyndi Lauper, Waylon Jennings,

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:49.740
when they all got together and
did "We are the World," at

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:52.360
Montessori school, you sing
it like twice a day.

00:15:52.360 --> 00:15:53.240
It would be like school
assembly.

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:54.320
And we'd be singing it.

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:55.310
And then it would be
in the afternoon.

00:15:55.310 --> 00:15:56.590
And you'd be singing it again.

00:15:56.590 --> 00:15:58.950
And I was so inspired by Michael
Jackson that I was

00:15:58.950 --> 00:16:01.210
like, I should write
a song of my own.

00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:03.240
If Michael Jackson writes about
Ethiopia, I'm going to

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:05.101
write about Ethiopia.

00:16:05.101 --> 00:16:05.600
[AUDIO PLAYBACK]

00:16:05.600 --> 00:16:13.384
-(SINGING) I want to help
a kid in Ethiopia.

00:16:13.384 --> 00:16:19.940
Nobody else can help this one.

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:21.840
MAJKA BURHARDT: He we go.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:26.760
-Everybody needs somebody.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:27.070
[END AUDIO PLAYBACK]

00:16:27.070 --> 00:16:27.170
MAJKA BURHARDT: See?

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:30.370
There's three and a half
more minutes of that.

00:16:30.370 --> 00:16:32.010
I'm sure you all wish
you could hear it.

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:36.885
I will make it available, pop it
up on my drive later on so

00:16:36.885 --> 00:16:38.910
you all can download it and
listen to it or torture

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:40.260
yourselves with it,
depending on what

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:41.550
you're thinking of doing.

00:16:41.550 --> 00:16:43.920
23 years later after I wrote
that song, I was

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:46.160
doing this in Ethiopia.

00:16:46.160 --> 00:16:49.190
And as I said, we thought we
were the smartest people in

00:16:49.190 --> 00:16:50.980
the world that we'd
figured this out.

00:16:50.980 --> 00:16:54.220
And it went incredibly well, to
climb, to put first ascents

00:16:54.220 --> 00:16:56.890
up on sandstone towers where
you're shoving your hands and

00:16:56.890 --> 00:16:57.830
your feet into cracks.

00:16:57.830 --> 00:16:58.710
And they're getting purchase.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:01.380
And you're putting your
equipment and your metal gear.

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:02.350
And you're clipping
your rope in.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:03.570
And you're pretty sure
it's going to keep

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:04.819
you safe if you fall.

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:07.190
And it went great
for like a day.

00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:09.720
And then it went
horribly wrong.

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:10.710
So here's the difference.

00:17:10.710 --> 00:17:11.819
It's going great on the left.

00:17:11.819 --> 00:17:12.990
It's a really cool photo.

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:14.750
On the right, it's a
really bad photo.

00:17:14.750 --> 00:17:16.400
This is sort of the difference
in what happened.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:18.430
Because there was professional
photographer Gabe taking

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:19.400
photos when we were happy.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:21.599
And there was Mike is very
scared and doesn't want to die

00:17:21.599 --> 00:17:23.839
in Ethiopia on the right
side of the screen.

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:25.930
Because what happened is this
crack that we were following--

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:27.819
we were trying to climb
this 500 foot tower.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:28.770
The crack disappeared.

00:17:28.770 --> 00:17:30.570
And suddenly, we just had
the face to climb.

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:32.980
And the rock that we were
climbing there was the kind of

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:35.630
rock that if you went up, you
could snap off the face hold

00:17:35.630 --> 00:17:37.210
with your finger, with
your pinkie.

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:39.550
You felt like if you just stared
at it for too long, it

00:17:39.550 --> 00:17:42.450
would return back to its
natural sand state.

00:17:42.450 --> 00:17:45.340
And that was all we had to go
on when this crack ended.

00:17:45.340 --> 00:17:48.370
And it was a point for me in my
climbing career that I was

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:50.580
like, wow, I don't even know
if I want to do this.

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:52.730
But I'm writing a book about
climbing in Ethiopia.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:54.940
And if I can't get beyond here,
what kind of book is

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:55.940
this going to be?

00:17:55.940 --> 00:17:57.000
And I ended up doing it.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.460
And we got to the top
of this climb.

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:01.090
And when we got to the top of
it, I was like, OK, now what?

00:18:01.090 --> 00:18:02.110
How are we going to get down?

00:18:02.110 --> 00:18:03.690
And I'm probably going to
have to do this again.

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:05.810
Because last I checked, it
wasn't a children's book that

00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:07.280
I signed a book deal for.

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:09.080
So I'm probably going to have
to climb more than one of

00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:09.780
these things.

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:12.330
And I'm scared about how
I'm going to do it.

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:14.630
This was the safe and
known route for me.

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:15.990
Coffee was supposed to
be overwhelming.

00:18:15.990 --> 00:18:18.390
Climbing was supposed to be
what would be easy for me.

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:20.590
And yet, when we got down from
climbing this tower--

00:18:20.590 --> 00:18:22.390
we did our first ascent
on that--

00:18:22.390 --> 00:18:24.570
we started hanging out with
a family at the base.

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:25.860
And this is a 14--

00:18:25.860 --> 00:18:28.980
excuse me, a 13-year-old girl
with her 4-month-old daughter

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:30.250
on her back.

00:18:30.250 --> 00:18:34.070
So here I am thinking about
exploring a country through

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:36.270
climbing, through opportunity,
through adventure.

00:18:36.270 --> 00:18:37.810
And then at the other side,
I'm looking at one of the

00:18:37.810 --> 00:18:40.370
highest needs for maternal
health care in the world.

00:18:40.370 --> 00:18:42.110
How do you put those
things together?

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:43.520
And how was I going to
put those things

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:44.590
together in the book?

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:46.740
And the only way that I figured
out how to do it was

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:49.450
to get comfortable with what I
now think about as the middle

00:18:49.450 --> 00:18:51.250
place, where some things
make sense.

00:18:51.250 --> 00:18:53.250
And some things never do.

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:55.970
Where that climbing and that
need for maternal health care

00:18:55.970 --> 00:18:57.530
can go together.

00:18:57.530 --> 00:19:01.865
Back in 2007, I never thought
I would go back to Ethiopia.

00:19:01.865 --> 00:19:02.830
I thought, I went there.

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:03.760
I had a really good time.

00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:04.620
I spent four months.

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:05.610
I wrote a book.

00:19:05.610 --> 00:19:08.360
But then I went on a speaking
tour for 50 cities when my

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:10.360
first book "Vertical
Ethiopia" came out.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:13.780
And I tried to tell these really
big complex stories

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:15.970
about Ethiopia from
that middle place.

00:19:15.970 --> 00:19:19.330
And what I saw is that people
wanted to know more.

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:21.060
And they would come up
to me afterwards.

00:19:21.060 --> 00:19:23.810
And they would be like, hey,
so about that coffee?

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:24.690
What's the deal with that?

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:26.120
Whatever happened to that?

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:28.630
Have you ever gone back and
thought more about that?

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:31.280
And pretty soon, I saw that
two things were going on.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:33.560
Number one, people really
like coffee.

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:34.300
That's kind of obvious.

00:19:34.300 --> 00:19:35.990
But it became very clear
to me at that point.

00:19:35.990 --> 00:19:38.920
And number two, we're sort of
obsessed with Ethiopia.

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:40.930
And part of that-- it's like if
I had written my first book

00:19:40.930 --> 00:19:43.770
about the Ivory Coast, it
probably wouldn't have been on

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:45.170
a 50 city speaking tour.

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:48.510
But we've all been trained to
pay attention to Ethiopia from

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:51.230
global media, in part because of
what happened in the '80s,

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:54.530
in part because it just became
this relative point for us to

00:19:54.530 --> 00:19:58.210
all cast off of in its aid
center of gravity, but also

00:19:58.210 --> 00:20:00.080
because of the ancient Aksumite

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:02.030
empire, Haile Selassie.

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:03.210
It's the only country in Africa

00:20:03.210 --> 00:20:04.230
that was never colonized.

00:20:04.230 --> 00:20:06.780
It has this rich history.

00:20:06.780 --> 00:20:08.950
We've just been taught to
pay attention to it.

00:20:08.950 --> 00:20:12.050
And I started thinking about,
well, how can I leverage that

00:20:12.050 --> 00:20:12.980
for Ethiopia?

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:15.550
What's going to be the most
interesting and enticing way

00:20:15.550 --> 00:20:16.670
that I can do it?

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:17.450
And I went back.

00:20:17.450 --> 00:20:19.250
And I was back in the States.

00:20:19.250 --> 00:20:20.880
And this is not Ethiopia.

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:23.120
This is New Hampshire, which is
where I went that winter to

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:25.350
go ice climbing, in 2008.

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:26.780
And while I was there, I was
like, I'm going to go back.

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:27.490
What's my plan?

00:20:27.490 --> 00:20:29.740
And I decided that I would go
back and write a book about

00:20:29.740 --> 00:20:32.150
coffee and culture and
connecting those two things to

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:34.260
try to tell a broader story
about Ethiopia.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:35.630
And then something
else happened.

00:20:35.630 --> 00:20:37.880
I got a phone call.

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:39.450
This is Imagine 1 Day.

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:43.550
Imagine 1 Day is a Canadian
nonprofit that is basically a

00:20:43.550 --> 00:20:46.420
leadership development
powerhouse in Ethiopia veiled

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:48.810
as an education nonprofit.

00:20:48.810 --> 00:20:51.310
And Image 1 Day had this idea
that they were going to go

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:53.990
into Ethiopia and support
primary school education.

00:20:53.990 --> 00:20:55.420
And that's how they
started out.

00:20:55.420 --> 00:20:58.400
But last year, they were working
in Bale, which is in

00:20:58.400 --> 00:20:59.960
south central Ethiopia.

00:20:59.960 --> 00:21:01.370
And they working with
their teachers.

00:21:01.370 --> 00:21:03.730
And they're working
on what they're

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:04.530
going to teach in schools.

00:21:04.530 --> 00:21:07.200
But they're also doing this
whole life skills training.

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:09.480
So they're talking to them about
communication skills,

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:10.710
about goal setting.

00:21:10.710 --> 00:21:14.430
And these teachers flooded the
Bale chapter of the Commercial

00:21:14.430 --> 00:21:17.260
Bank of Ethiopia and opened bank
accounts the day after

00:21:17.260 --> 00:21:19.670
this life skills training
happened so much so that the

00:21:19.670 --> 00:21:22.170
Commercial Bank of Ethiopia
called Imagine 1 Day and was

00:21:22.170 --> 00:21:23.820
like, um, who are you?

00:21:23.820 --> 00:21:24.690
What are you doing?

00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:27.240
We've never had teachers open
savings account like

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:28.800
this in this area.

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:32.190
Imagine 1 Day, up in the north
of Ethiopia, they have this

00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:34.970
great scholarship program
for high school kids.

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:36.930
They wanted to work in
primary education.

00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:37.900
Now they're giving scholarships

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:38.890
to high school kids.

00:21:38.890 --> 00:21:40.510
And they're doing it where
they're like, you, you're

00:21:40.510 --> 00:21:41.320
super motivated.

00:21:41.320 --> 00:21:42.970
So I'm going to give
you a loan.

00:21:42.970 --> 00:21:45.360
Because in Ethiopia, to go to
high school, it's basically

00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:46.380
like going to boarding school.

00:21:46.380 --> 00:21:47.550
Because you're going
to have to travel.

00:21:47.550 --> 00:21:49.410
You're not going to have it
in your remote village.

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:51.550
So in order for you to have
the money to go to school,

00:21:51.550 --> 00:21:52.820
we're going to give
you seed money.

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:53.610
Get your supplies.

00:21:53.610 --> 00:21:55.410
And we're going to give your
parents a loan to buy a really

00:21:55.410 --> 00:21:56.590
skinny cow.

00:21:56.590 --> 00:21:58.310
And then your parents are
going to feed that cow.

00:21:58.310 --> 00:21:58.980
And they're going
to have a whole

00:21:58.980 --> 00:22:00.400
animal fattening program.

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:01.620
They're going to sell
that fat cow.

00:22:01.620 --> 00:22:02.810
They're going to save
some money.

00:22:02.810 --> 00:22:04.110
They're going to buy some
more skinny cows.

00:22:04.110 --> 00:22:07.120
And at the end of four years,
these parents are going to

00:22:07.120 --> 00:22:09.540
have actually financed three
years of that kid's high

00:22:09.540 --> 00:22:10.350
school education.

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:11.910
And the one year that
Imagine 1 Day did

00:22:11.910 --> 00:22:13.470
is going to be forgiven.

00:22:13.470 --> 00:22:16.650
This is a program that this
was never their intention.

00:22:16.650 --> 00:22:18.680
This was completely outside
of their wheelhouse.

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:22.010
What the heck is a nonprofit
focused in education doing

00:22:22.010 --> 00:22:28.020
fattening 177 cows and opening
497 bank accounts and working

00:22:28.020 --> 00:22:31.170
with schools and going to some
of the poorest people in the

00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:33.060
world and saying, you
want a school?

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:33.690
That's great.

00:22:33.690 --> 00:22:35.120
Help us pay for it.

00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:36.570
Asking the poorest people
in the world to

00:22:36.570 --> 00:22:38.000
actually spend money.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.930
And that's part of what Imagine
1 Day does is they're

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:41.240
like, what do you want?

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:42.770
Can you help us get there?

00:22:42.770 --> 00:22:45.320
And what they've seen is a
resounding yes from these

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:46.250
communities in Ethiopia.

00:22:46.250 --> 00:22:47.910
Like, we want to help.

00:22:47.910 --> 00:22:50.480
You have communities who go
and petition the cement

00:22:50.480 --> 00:22:53.530
companies nearby and say,
we really need a road.

00:22:53.530 --> 00:22:55.280
And those communities
created that road.

00:22:55.280 --> 00:22:56.750
It wasn't Imagine 1
Day who did that.

00:22:56.750 --> 00:22:58.010
It was the community.

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:02.540
And there are examples of this
happening throughout Ethiopia

00:23:02.540 --> 00:23:03.960
with these non-profits.

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:06.580
And part of it is because you
have this confluence.

00:23:06.580 --> 00:23:09.050
So many people flooded
to Ethiopia in the

00:23:09.050 --> 00:23:10.260
'80s and the '90s.

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:13.110
And so many people were doing a
very large and messy version

00:23:13.110 --> 00:23:15.670
of aid that it was bound to
happen that people were going

00:23:15.670 --> 00:23:17.880
to start getting streamlined
and working towards

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:19.910
sustainable development.

00:23:19.910 --> 00:23:23.100
When Imagine 1 Day gave me a
call in 2008, we were like, we

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:24.030
need to work together.

00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:27.130
Because what we're both trying
to do is somehow change the

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:29.290
conversation about Ethiopia.

00:23:29.290 --> 00:23:31.690
And we're here in the US.

00:23:31.690 --> 00:23:33.920
There's a pretty international
crowd in this room and the

00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:35.620
people that I've talked
to already.

00:23:35.620 --> 00:23:39.600
We all know what national
identity is on a global scale,

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.700
that countries are
misrepresented and

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:45.050
misunderstood constantly in
our world and truncated to

00:23:45.050 --> 00:23:47.700
become smaller and
easier to digest.

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:49.900
And we thought, if we can help
change the conversation about

00:23:49.900 --> 00:23:52.720
Ethiopia, where are those
conversation shifts going to

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:55.920
be more important on the global
scale down the road?

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:57.800
I've since worked with
Imagine 1 Day.

00:23:57.800 --> 00:24:01.830
We've combined rock climbing,
education, coffee, eye care,

00:24:01.830 --> 00:24:03.970
all of these different ways
to keep blowing it out.

00:24:03.970 --> 00:24:06.820
And a lot of non-profits
will approach me.

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:07.760
And they're like, we want
to work with you.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:09.780
And one of the first questions
I say is, are you willing to

00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:11.390
go outside your wheelhouse?

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:14.960
Because non-profits have had a
focus for a long time about

00:24:14.960 --> 00:24:16.810
saying, this is the one
thing I'm going to do.

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:19.500
I'm going to make sure that
I'm focused on foot care.

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:21.160
Because foot care is the
way that people are

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:21.920
going to move around.

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:22.540
And it's going--

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:23.810
whatever my mandate is.

00:24:23.810 --> 00:24:26.310
But if there isn't
collaboration, if people

00:24:26.310 --> 00:24:28.380
aren't saying, in order to do
this, then I need to work with

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:29.610
the schools, and I'm
going to work with

00:24:29.610 --> 00:24:31.170
the health care systems.

00:24:31.170 --> 00:24:32.510
Then these things die.

00:24:32.510 --> 00:24:36.290
And these things die a really
long death that gives aid the

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:37.920
bad name that it kind of had.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:41.060
And it's really fascinating to
me that if you take a country,

00:24:41.060 --> 00:24:43.660
like Ethiopia, that was once,
like I said, that largest

00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:46.870
recipient of aid in sub-Saharan
Africa, what if we

00:24:46.870 --> 00:24:49.540
could kick total butt on
sustainable development and be

00:24:49.540 --> 00:24:50.780
the leader for that?

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:53.330
Wouldn't that be one of the
greatest things to come out of

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:56.130
what's happened in Ethiopia
in the past 30 years?

00:24:56.130 --> 00:24:58.120
It's not super easy.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:00.260
And one thing that I will
definitely admit is Ethiopia

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:01.350
is not a perfect country.

00:25:01.350 --> 00:25:04.690
I mean, no one in this room
can come up with a country

00:25:04.690 --> 00:25:05.820
that's perfect.

00:25:05.820 --> 00:25:07.170
But that's sort of the point.

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:09.400
And I like to think Ethiopian
is like the ultimate

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:12.500
doppelganger for all
of us in the world.

00:25:12.500 --> 00:25:15.430
And if it can succeed, then
we can succeed at this

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:16.400
complexity.

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:18.660
And for me, that all comes
back to coffee.

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:21.840
And the reason it does is
because in Ethiopia, you have

00:25:21.840 --> 00:25:25.160
80 languages, 200 dialects,
10,000 types of coffee.

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:28.420
Multiply that all, do some extra
numeric, get to infinite

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:33.130
numbers of stories about
coffee and complexity.

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:35.380
And in Ethiopia, when you
drink coffee, you

00:25:35.380 --> 00:25:37.630
drink it as a ritual.

00:25:37.630 --> 00:25:40.000
You drink it as a way to
celebrate your culture.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:41.860
And the stories that
there are abound.

00:25:41.860 --> 00:25:44.510
This is a guy named Gebru who
lives up in northern Ethiopia.

00:25:44.510 --> 00:25:47.380
And he told me that when he was
growing up, he was told if

00:25:47.380 --> 00:25:50.510
he drank coffee, he wouldn't
make it to paradise or heaven.

00:25:50.510 --> 00:25:53.120
And the proof from his parents
came in the following story.

00:25:53.120 --> 00:25:56.250
That when Jesus was
killed, coffee

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:58.210
didn't mourn Jesus properly.

00:25:58.210 --> 00:26:01.500
So when Jesus was killed, the
Earth went into mourning.

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:03.110
So the rivers were dry.

00:26:03.110 --> 00:26:07.030
The trees were completely
barren.

00:26:07.030 --> 00:26:08.420
The wind was still.

00:26:08.420 --> 00:26:12.470
But the only plant that kept
growing was the coffee plant.

00:26:12.470 --> 00:26:13.760
It sprouted new leaves.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:15.070
It had fresh cherries.

00:26:15.070 --> 00:26:18.410
Coffee, as Gebru says,
didn't cry for Jesus.

00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:21.140
So he wasn't allowed to drink
it when he was growing up.

00:26:21.140 --> 00:26:23.800
He told me this story over a cup
of coffee in his mid '40s.

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:25.730
So clearly, we've moved
on from this.

00:26:25.730 --> 00:26:27.940
He thinks he still has a decent
shot at paradise.

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:30.780
But most of the kids in his
generation didn't drink coffee

00:26:30.780 --> 00:26:33.410
growing up but then kind of
moved on to having it when

00:26:33.410 --> 00:26:35.240
they got older.

00:26:35.240 --> 00:26:38.180
A couple hours south of where
Gebru is in northern Ethiopia,

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:40.940
on the shores of Lake Tana,
there's a place called the

00:26:40.940 --> 00:26:45.370
Zegay Peninsula where in 1307
Bishop Abuna Mariam gathered

00:26:45.370 --> 00:26:46.310
his flock of people.

00:26:46.310 --> 00:26:47.490
And they settled there.

00:26:47.490 --> 00:26:48.870
And they said, what are
we going to do?

00:26:48.870 --> 00:26:49.435
How are we going to survive?

00:26:49.435 --> 00:26:50.770
And he said, don't
worry about it.

00:26:50.770 --> 00:26:51.805
And he took his prayer stick.

00:26:51.805 --> 00:26:53.750
And he broke it across
his leg.

00:26:53.750 --> 00:26:55.520
And he planted one piece
in the ground.

00:26:55.520 --> 00:26:57.670
And he broke it again and
planted two more pieces.

00:26:57.670 --> 00:26:59.260
And he said, come
back tomorrow.

00:26:59.260 --> 00:27:00.450
So everybody came back
the next day.

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:01.850
And there were three
crops growing,

00:27:01.850 --> 00:27:04.180
coffee, hops, and lemon.

00:27:04.180 --> 00:27:06.860
And the bishop made his people
promise that those were the

00:27:06.860 --> 00:27:09.590
only crops that they
would ever have

00:27:09.590 --> 00:27:10.800
on the Zegay Peninsula.

00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:13.100
And to this day-- this
was in 1307.

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:15.280
To this day, those are
the only crops grown

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:16.550
on the Zegay Peninsula.

00:27:16.550 --> 00:27:19.660
And they're transported across
Lake Tana on these papyrus

00:27:19.660 --> 00:27:22.150
boats every day.

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:24.490
Coffee origin stories
abound in Ethiopia.

00:27:24.490 --> 00:27:26.360
Like I said, we have the
multiplier, right?

00:27:26.360 --> 00:27:28.280
A friend of mine once said
that if you flew over

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.710
Ethiopia, and you had a lot of
gentle darts, just like little

00:27:31.710 --> 00:27:32.945
stickies or something
like that that

00:27:32.945 --> 00:27:33.890
had a little traction.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:35.860
And you just dropped them.

00:27:35.860 --> 00:27:37.920
Every place they landed, you'd
have a new story about coffee

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:38.680
in Ethiopia.

00:27:38.680 --> 00:27:40.080
And that's probably true.

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:42.550
Have any of you guys heard
of the story of Khaldi?

00:27:42.550 --> 00:27:46.620
So Khaldi, there's a very famous
story that if coffee

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:48.530
comes from Ethiopia, there
was a guy named Khaldi.

00:27:48.530 --> 00:27:49.105
He's Christian.

00:27:49.105 --> 00:27:49.700
He's Muslim.

00:27:49.700 --> 00:27:50.620
He's a delinquent.

00:27:50.620 --> 00:27:51.250
He's a scholar.

00:27:51.250 --> 00:27:52.780
There's lots of different
variations.

00:27:52.780 --> 00:27:54.750
The bottom line is, Khaldi
saw some goats having

00:27:54.750 --> 00:27:55.920
a really good time.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:57.830
And he's like, that looks fun.

00:27:57.830 --> 00:27:59.390
And he went and was like,
wow, they're having fun.

00:27:59.390 --> 00:28:01.410
Because there were
eating coffee.

00:28:01.410 --> 00:28:03.430
So he started eating coffee,
brewing coffee.

00:28:03.430 --> 00:28:04.940
Boom, coffee.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:07.340
Khaldi, most stories,
is from Kaffa.

00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:10.735
Kaffa is a region, the kind
of kingdom of Kaffa in the

00:28:10.735 --> 00:28:11.530
central Ethiopia.

00:28:11.530 --> 00:28:15.260
And it's a great onomatopoeic
link to say Kaffa, coffee,

00:28:15.260 --> 00:28:16.460
which is not actually true.

00:28:16.460 --> 00:28:17.410
It's a really cool story.

00:28:17.410 --> 00:28:20.230
But coffee, the word, comes from
the Arabic word Qahwa,

00:28:20.230 --> 00:28:23.300
which is a drink made
from the brew.

00:28:23.300 --> 00:28:25.550
There's a great story about
the seventh century coffee

00:28:25.550 --> 00:28:28.150
being discovered by Prophet
Muhammad's grandsons.

00:28:28.150 --> 00:28:29.690
His mother was giving
them a bath.

00:28:29.690 --> 00:28:31.400
And she tossed their bath
water out the window.

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:34.390
And the next morning, a coffee
forest had sprung up there.

00:28:34.390 --> 00:28:37.310
And that began the Muslim
ritual, in Ethiopia, of using

00:28:37.310 --> 00:28:39.670
coffee beans for ceremonial
purposes.

00:28:39.670 --> 00:28:42.750
There's a story about a ox
that smelled really good.

00:28:42.750 --> 00:28:43.820
And he started coffee.

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:44.920
Because he smelled good.

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:46.890
And people wanted to smell
as good as the ox.

00:28:46.890 --> 00:28:48.700
There's no right story.

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:51.110
And that's part of the beauty
of the way stories are

00:28:51.110 --> 00:28:52.670
expressed in Ethiopia.

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:54.240
And when you have coffee,
that's your

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:55.390
time to share that.

00:28:55.390 --> 00:28:58.340
Coffee is usually drunk in a
three step ritual called a

00:28:58.340 --> 00:28:59.480
coffee ceremony.

00:28:59.480 --> 00:29:01.620
So when I was with Marsha Aday,
the coffee I didn't get

00:29:01.620 --> 00:29:04.730
to drink, Gete Tebo, his wife,
was making the first cup of

00:29:04.730 --> 00:29:07.050
coffee, super, super
strong coffee.

00:29:07.050 --> 00:29:09.700
And once we all had that, she'd
pour water into that

00:29:09.700 --> 00:29:11.630
same pot and re-brew it.

00:29:11.630 --> 00:29:13.620
And then we'd have a second
weaker cup and then a third

00:29:13.620 --> 00:29:14.740
weaker cup.

00:29:14.740 --> 00:29:17.350
And in the Amaro Mountains, if
you show up in the first cup

00:29:17.350 --> 00:29:20.330
of coffee, and there's an
unmarried woman who's in that

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:22.160
house and you cross the
threshold during the first

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:24.140
cup, she's yours.

00:29:24.140 --> 00:29:25.850
Marriages have been brokered
