00:39:11.420 --> 00:39:13.760
you're trying to do.

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:16.840
When you step over into press
freedom, Ethiopia is not-- if

00:39:16.840 --> 00:39:18.140
it's like, let's make
more journalists.

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:19.540
That's not really going
to be supported

00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:20.720
that well right there.

00:39:20.720 --> 00:39:23.380
But the same thing with like
internet access or the way

00:39:23.380 --> 00:39:25.780
that texting works
in Ethiopia.

00:39:25.780 --> 00:39:29.190
But I think that one of the
things that the Ethiopian

00:39:29.190 --> 00:39:32.190
government is really trying to
spearhead is actually wanting

00:39:32.190 --> 00:39:32.980
to be that progressive.

00:39:32.980 --> 00:39:35.580
If you set a mandate that you
want to be a middle income

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:38.430
country in a very short amount
of time, then you're going to

00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:40.550
have to be willing for people
to get in and kind of get

00:39:40.550 --> 00:39:43.090
grisly and dirty with how
they're going to do it.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:45.850
And they've been really
supportive, I think, to a lot

00:39:45.850 --> 00:39:49.110
of sustainable development
groups.

00:39:49.110 --> 00:39:51.030
Sustainable development is one
of those things that's almost

00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:53.410
becoming a phrase that doesn't
mean anything anymore.

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:55.190
And I think that's really
unfortunate.

00:39:55.190 --> 00:39:56.820
Because it's a big difference.

00:39:56.820 --> 00:39:59.180
Sustainable development
and aid are on other

00:39:59.180 --> 00:40:00.380
sides of the spectrum.

00:40:00.380 --> 00:40:03.380
And I'd love to see us have that
word not fall away and

00:40:03.380 --> 00:40:04.610
become like, nah, whatever.

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:08.300
But actually support that word
and ask people what it means,

00:40:08.300 --> 00:40:10.950
what it means to extract
yourself from somewhere, what

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:14.350
it means to have these schools
support themselves because

00:40:14.350 --> 00:40:18.320
they have income generating
strategies for schools.

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:20.320
There's this great group I work
with called the Himalayan

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:21.090
Cataract Project.

00:40:21.090 --> 00:40:23.680
Horrible name for a group
working all over the world.

00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:24.930
But they do eye care.

00:40:24.930 --> 00:40:28.500
And when they do eye care in
Ethiopia, they've trained tons

00:40:28.500 --> 00:40:31.470
of nurses and local surgeons
to do these cataract

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:34.000
interventions so that they come
in and bolster it and

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:35.070
more numbers happen.

00:40:35.070 --> 00:40:37.990
But it's being self-sustained
in Ethiopia.

00:40:37.990 --> 00:40:39.590
AUDIENCE: How are you seeing
sustainable development work

00:40:39.590 --> 00:40:40.730
out in Ethiopia?

00:40:40.730 --> 00:40:43.710
Coffee has a really long
history and tradition,

00:40:43.710 --> 00:40:47.040
especially in Brazil, of really
not being sustainable.

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:48.730
So are there organizations?

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:51.870
Or how are people learning to
become sustainable farmers or

00:40:51.870 --> 00:40:55.460
build a sustainable
food chain?

00:40:55.460 --> 00:40:57.280
MAJKA BURHARDT: When you
bring up Brazil--

00:40:57.280 --> 00:40:58.720
it's sort of Ethiopia's
blessing

00:40:58.720 --> 00:40:59.860
because of its history.

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:01.460
Because it wasn't
industrialized.

00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:04.280
Because it wasn't using massive
amounts of chemicals.

00:41:04.280 --> 00:41:05.790
Because everything wasn't
getting poured in the same

00:41:05.790 --> 00:41:08.810
place, it kind of has a bit of
a weird advantage to that.

00:41:08.810 --> 00:41:12.700
But when we're talking about
sustainability on that level,

00:41:12.700 --> 00:41:15.310
there's a lot of work
being done to that.

00:41:15.310 --> 00:41:17.190
It's been really difficult
in Ethiopia.

00:41:17.190 --> 00:41:18.900
It's probably the same thing
in the Bay Area, right?

00:41:18.900 --> 00:41:19.850
You have a really small farm.

00:41:19.850 --> 00:41:21.670
They want to get an organic
certification.

00:41:21.670 --> 00:41:24.480
The money they have to pay to
get an organic certification

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:25.774
is really prohibitive.

00:41:25.774 --> 00:41:28.560
So there have been different
coffee companies that will go

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:30.860
in and be like, we'll
cover this.

00:41:30.860 --> 00:41:32.910
Or you guys get your
Rainforest Alliance

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:33.500
certification.

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:34.900
And we'll help you work
through that.

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:37.430
Because the rest of the world
wants to see that stamp and

00:41:37.430 --> 00:41:39.650
wants to know that you're going
through those practices.

00:41:39.650 --> 00:41:42.460
I would say that a lot of the
coffee grown in Ethiopia

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:45.580
already sort of falls under
sustainable practices.

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:50.160
But it's about actually being
cognizant and focused on

00:41:50.160 --> 00:41:53.730
continuing it as things start to
get industrialized and also

00:41:53.730 --> 00:41:55.120
as money starts coming
in for coffee.

00:41:55.120 --> 00:41:57.330
Because once you get more money,
it's like, let's grow

00:41:57.330 --> 00:41:58.230
the coffee faster.

00:41:58.230 --> 00:41:59.100
Let's get it going.

00:41:59.100 --> 00:41:59.570
It's like, whoa.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:01.130
Actually, we need to
go the slow way.

00:42:01.130 --> 00:42:03.530
Because that's going to
be where that value is

00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:04.130
going to come in.

00:42:04.130 --> 00:42:06.710
So there's a fair amount of
agricultural support.

00:42:06.710 --> 00:42:08.760
It's an agrarian country.

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:09.910
So you have that.

00:42:09.910 --> 00:42:11.060
And it's an interesting thing.

00:42:11.060 --> 00:42:13.380
Because there's actually a lot
of intervention from China

00:42:13.380 --> 00:42:15.460
right now, especially
in the roads and the

00:42:15.460 --> 00:42:17.840
telecommunications industry
in Ethiopia.

00:42:17.840 --> 00:42:20.700
And then as that starts to bleed
into agriculture, where

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:24.450
those kind of sustainable
mandates, where they hold up

00:42:24.450 --> 00:42:25.120
and when they don't.

00:42:25.120 --> 00:42:27.740
And I'm really curious to see
where Ethiopia is going to

00:42:27.740 --> 00:42:30.530
fall on that in the
next couple years.

00:42:30.530 --> 00:42:33.750
AUDIENCE: How does fair trade
play into the economics of

00:42:33.750 --> 00:42:34.890
coffee in Ethiopia?

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:38.410
And what do Ethiopians
think of fair trade?

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:41.390
MAJKA BURHARDT: My favorite and
least favorite question.

00:42:41.390 --> 00:42:44.280
So fair trade's complicated.

00:42:44.280 --> 00:42:46.580
Because fair trade is like
this great idea, right?

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:47.840
And I use it as an example.

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:49.580
When I first went to Ethiopia,
I'm like, fair trade,

00:42:49.580 --> 00:42:51.460
organic, let's go.

00:42:51.460 --> 00:42:53.910
And then when you get into the
nitty-gritty of it, you

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:56.460
realize that fair trade can
sometimes be a limiter.

00:42:56.460 --> 00:42:57.970
Because fair trade
sets a price.

00:42:57.970 --> 00:42:59.960
And then sometimes those farmers
can't get more than

00:42:59.960 --> 00:43:00.870
that for their coffee.

00:43:00.870 --> 00:43:05.160
So it kind of has this back end
limitation involved in it.

00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:09.830
So in Ethiopia, fair trade
initially was seen as

00:43:09.830 --> 00:43:10.860
something that was
really great.

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:12.470
Because it meant that you got
a little bit more money for

00:43:12.470 --> 00:43:13.540
your coffee.

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:16.030
But now it's seen as,
how can we make

00:43:16.030 --> 00:43:17.570
fair trade more flexible?

00:43:17.570 --> 00:43:20.530
Because that's how fair trade
has to evolve to be most

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.310
effective for some
of these products

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:24.360
as opposed to saying--

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:26.655
the fair trade price does
fluctuate depending on what

00:43:26.655 --> 00:43:27.800
the commodity price is.

00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:30.330
But it doesn't allow for the
price to be like crazy because

00:43:30.330 --> 00:43:33.550
all of a sudden people tasted
this one coffee and think that

00:43:33.550 --> 00:43:35.600
it should get $95 a pound.

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:36.880
It doesn't accommodate
for that.

00:43:36.880 --> 00:43:39.680
So how can we kind of use
fair trade would be my

00:43:39.680 --> 00:43:41.130
recommendation and use--

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:42.540
it has such a hold
over people.

00:43:42.540 --> 00:43:43.480
It's amazing.

00:43:43.480 --> 00:43:45.410
We see it as a stamp.

00:43:45.410 --> 00:43:46.460
Like when you buy things,
you're like,

00:43:46.460 --> 00:43:47.030
oh, it's fair trade.

00:43:47.030 --> 00:43:47.870
It's probably better.

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:49.860
It's been really effective
at its marketing.

00:43:49.860 --> 00:43:53.590
And I would say, if fair trade
can keep evolving so we can

00:43:53.590 --> 00:43:56.310
use that mind share it has, then
it's going to be the best

00:43:56.310 --> 00:43:57.980
circumstance for Ethiopia.

00:43:57.980 --> 00:44:01.120
AUDIENCE: You mentioned the
harmony between the Muslim and

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:03.680
Christian communities
in Ethiopia.

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:06.340
In almost all around the world,
there's some trouble in

00:44:06.340 --> 00:44:07.960
between the two.

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:10.580
What's the secret sauce?

00:44:10.580 --> 00:44:14.120
MAJKA BURHARDT: I think the
secret sauce in Ethiopia is

00:44:14.120 --> 00:44:15.770
that it's just mingled.

00:44:15.770 --> 00:44:19.240
I have a good friend named Teddy
Berhanu who I've worked

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:20.440
with on probably seven

00:44:20.440 --> 00:44:22.060
different projects in Ethiopia.

00:44:22.060 --> 00:44:23.540
And Teddy just tells
it how it is.

00:44:23.540 --> 00:44:26.500
This is a guy who at one point
was pulled over by some

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:28.990
militia dude with a
big machine gun.

00:44:28.990 --> 00:44:29.680
And he walked out.

00:44:29.680 --> 00:44:31.580
And he was so mad that
he went hand-to-hand

00:44:31.580 --> 00:44:32.590
combat with this guy.

00:44:32.590 --> 00:44:33.630
Got rid of the machine gun.

00:44:33.630 --> 00:44:34.150
Tied him up.

00:44:34.150 --> 00:44:35.550
Put him in the back
of his car.

00:44:35.550 --> 00:44:37.170
Drove him to the nearest
police station.

00:44:37.170 --> 00:44:38.460
That's Teddy.

00:44:38.460 --> 00:44:40.320
He's just like-- he's
like, [GRUNTS].

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:42.830
But he's kind of this little
really nice guy.

00:44:42.830 --> 00:44:45.140
And I always ask him about the
Muslim, Christian thing.

00:44:45.140 --> 00:44:46.640
And he's like, Majka,
whatever.

00:44:46.640 --> 00:44:47.470
I grew up.

00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:48.660
And it was my birthday.

00:44:48.660 --> 00:44:49.730
We would have my birthday.

00:44:49.730 --> 00:44:51.370
And then it was like,
oh, you're fasting.

00:44:51.370 --> 00:44:52.200
But I'm not fasting.

00:44:52.200 --> 00:44:55.660
So I'll make sure that your
Muslim father cuts

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:56.520
the meat for you.

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:58.830
And then when I come over, I
make sure that your Christian

00:44:58.830 --> 00:45:02.300
neighbor shows up and does
what I need to do.

00:45:02.300 --> 00:45:05.480
I think that there's just been
so much integration that it's

00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:06.450
worked really well.

00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:08.310
On the flip side of it, there
are parts of Ethiopia where

00:45:08.310 --> 00:45:09.160
that's not happening.

00:45:09.160 --> 00:45:10.880
And there's parts of
Ethiopia where that

00:45:10.880 --> 00:45:12.820
tension is being prodded.

00:45:12.820 --> 00:45:14.650
And that's really unfortunate.

00:45:14.650 --> 00:45:17.890
Because sometimes there are
reasons for tension because of

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:19.530
the way that assets have been

00:45:19.530 --> 00:45:21.200
allocated, land's been allocated.

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:23.400
But I actually think that quite
a bit, because of it's

00:45:23.400 --> 00:45:25.590
position in the Horn of
Africa, other groups

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:26.240
are going in there.

00:45:26.240 --> 00:45:29.050
There's a big insight in from
the Protestants groups trying

00:45:29.050 --> 00:45:30.540
to be like, let's
stir the ashes.

00:45:30.540 --> 00:45:32.000
Let's feed the fire
a little bit.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.700
And if anything, that's the
thing we should be fighting to

00:45:34.700 --> 00:45:36.020
not happen.

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:38.370
Because I think that--
it's like I said.

00:45:38.370 --> 00:45:40.980
There's so much diversity in
Ethiopia that it isn't really

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:42.680
about if you're Christian
or if you're Muslim.

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:44.780
It's really about, well,
what else you got?

00:45:44.780 --> 00:45:46.710
Because there's a lot more
things that make us different.

00:45:46.710 --> 00:45:49.050
And so it becomes less
relevant within that.

00:45:49.050 --> 00:45:53.280
And you just have that mapping
and continuous overlapping.

00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:55.170
AUDIENCE: Please, give
a hand to Majka.

00:45:55.170 --> 00:45:58.770
[APPLAUSE]

